The Democratic Republic of the Congo is currently facing its 17th Ebola outbreak, which was officially declared on May 15, 2026 . Unlike previous emergencies, this outbreak involves the Bundibugyo virus strain, for which there are no approved vaccines or specific treatments .

📊 Current Situation at a Glance

As of early June 2026, the outbreak has escalated significantly. Here is the latest data according to health officials :

· Confirmed Cases: 344 in DRC, plus 15 in neighboring Uganda.
· Confirmed Deaths: 60 in DRC, plus 1 in Uganda.
· Geographic Spread: Cases have been confirmed in three provinces—Ituri (epicenter), North Kivu, and South Kivu. It has also spread to Uganda .
· Global Risk: WHO currently assesses the risk as "low" at the global level, but "very high" nationally and "high" regionally .

🚨 Why This Outbreak Is Different

This situation is particularly challenging for three major reasons:

· No Vaccine or Therapeutics: The absence of approved medical countermeasures means responders cannot use the ring vaccination strategy that ended previous outbreaks. Containment relies entirely on classic public health measures like contact tracing and isolation .
· Delayed Detection & Testing Issues: The outbreak likely went undetected for weeks. Initial tests failed to identify the Bundibugyo strain because local machines were configured for the more common Zaire strain. This has resulted in a backlog of over 1,000 suspected cases that needed re-testing .
· Security & Trust: The outbreak is unfolding in a volatile region with active conflict and displacement. Critically, only 45% of contacts are currently being followed, well below the 90% needed to stop the spread, partly due to community mistrust .

🌍 The Response and International Action

The World Health Organization (WHO) declared a Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC) on May 17, just two days after the confirmation, to trigger global support .

· On the Ground: Organizations like MSF are building new treatment centers (including an 80-bed facility in Goma and a 65-bed center in Ituri) and training health workers .
· International Aid: China has dispatched a medical expert team for a three-month mission, while the CDC is assisting with surveillance and lab support . The Bunia airport has also reopened to passenger flights to restore supply chains .
· The Ultimate Goal: WHO Director-General Tedros noted that while stopping this outbreak is inevitable, preventing the 18th outbreak requires strengthening routine health services, as communities fear Ebola responses will drain resources from malaria and malnutrition care .

